<CaseStudy
  title="Computational Protein Binding of DMTS and DMDS"
  subtitle="Sam Houston State University · Lab Manager & Research Assistant · Aug 2023 – Aug 2025"
  tags={['Molecular Docking', 'AutoDock Vina', 'PyMOL', 'Protein Binding', 'PK Modeling']}
  year="2023 – 2025"
  description="Computational protein binding study of DMTS and DMDS using AutoDock Vina and PyMOL. Molecular docking for cyanide antidote research at Sam Houston State University. Aashni Khurana's computational chemistry work."
  prevStudy={{ title: 'iPSC-Derived Motor Neurons as a Model for Meditation-Induced Bloodborne Signaling', href: '/case-studies/ipsc-meditation' }}
  nextStudy={{ title: 'DMDS–Albumin Protein Binding', href: '/case-studies/dmds-experimental' }}
>

  <p>
    Wet-lab assays tell you whether a compound binds, but they are slow, volatile-compound binding is especially finicky (see <a href="/case-studies/dmds-experimental">DMDS–Albumin Protein Binding</a>), and they cannot tell you <em>where</em> on the protein surface the interaction is happening. To triangulate the experimental findings with a second, orthogonal line of evidence, I carried out molecular docking studies on both dimethyl trisulfide (DMTS) and its metabolite dimethyl disulfide (DMDS) against bovine serum albumin (BSA), the structural analog of human albumin commonly used in early-stage binding work.
  </p>

  <p>
    I built the docking grids in AutoDock Vina (full-protein blind docking, exhaustiveness level 8, energy range 4), configured to let the algorithm search the entire BSA surface for thermodynamically favorable binding sites without any priors about where those sites might be. Nine poses per ligand were generated, ranked by predicted binding affinity.
  </p>

  <div class="cs-image-wrap">
    <img
      src="/images/thesis/08_binding_affinity_dmts.jpg"
      alt="Top DMTS binding pose on bovine serum albumin surface, rendered as ribbon diagram in PyMOL, showing predicted binding site"
    />
    <p class="cs-caption">DMTS BINDING POSE ON BOVINE SERUM ALBUMIN</p>
  </div>

  <div class="cs-image-wrap">
    <img
      src="/images/thesis/09_binding_affinity_dmds.jpg"
      alt="Top DMDS binding pose on bovine serum albumin surface, rendered as ribbon diagram in PyMOL, showing predicted binding site"
    />
    <p class="cs-caption">DMDS BINDING POSE ON BOVINE SERUM ALBUMIN</p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Best-scoring poses came in at &minus;2.6 kcal/mol for DMTS and &minus;2.3 kcal/mol for DMDS. These are weak binding energies by small-molecule standards, and importantly, they are consistent with the weak affinity observed experimentally in the Vapor Transfer Equilibrium (VTE) and Rapid Equilibrium Dialysis (RED) assays. The computational result corroborated the wet-lab one: two independent methods, one conclusion.
  </p>

  <div class="cs-image-grid">
    <div class="cs-image-wrap">
      <img
        src="/images/thesis/06_dmts_poses_animation.gif"
        alt="Multiple docking poses for DMTS on bovine serum albumin surface, showing candidate binding geometries generated by AutoDock Vina"
      />
      <p class="cs-caption">MULTIPLE DOCKING POSES (DMTS)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cs-image-wrap">
      <img
        src="/images/thesis/07_dmds_poses_animation.gif"
        alt="Multiple docking poses for DMDS on bovine serum albumin surface, showing candidate binding geometries generated by AutoDock Vina"
      />
      <p class="cs-caption">MULTIPLE DOCKING POSES (DMDS)</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    The multiple-pose analysis was the part that made the work genuinely useful to the broader program. Both ligands clustered at structurally similar regions of the albumin surface, suggesting that DMTS and DMDS engage the protein through a shared set of interaction geometries rather than distinct mechanisms. For a drug development pipeline where DMTS is the administered molecule and DMDS is the in-vivo metabolite, that shared-binding pattern matters: it means the pharmacokinetic behavior of the parent compound and its active metabolite is likely governed by the same transport mechanism, simplifying the PK modeling.
  </p>

  <p>
    I visualized all poses in PyMOL and generated the ribbon-diagram figures used in the thesis. Beyond the specific result, this project was my first real exposure to computational modeling, and it sharpened a question I keep coming back to: where can computational methods extend, or calibrate, what is achievable on the bench?
  </p>

